{"id":"2111.06569","submitter":"Lintao Li","authors":"Lintao Li, Wei Chen, and Khaled B. Letaief","title":"Bounding Queue Length Violation Probability of Joint Channel and Buffer\n  Aware Transmission","comments":"This is the full version of the conference paper which has been\n  submitted to ICC 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT eess.SP math.IT","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Queue length violation probability, i.e., the tail distribution of the queue\nlength, is a widely used statistical quality-of-service (QoS) metric in\nwireless communications. Characterizing and optimizing the queue length\nviolation probability have great significance in time sensitive networking\n(TSN) and ultra reliable and low-latency communications (URLLC). However, it\nstill remains an open problem. In this paper, we put our focus on the analysis\nof the tail distribution of the queue length from the perspective of\ncross-layer design in wireless link transmission. We find that, under the\nfinite average power consumption constraint, the queue length violation\nprobability can achieve zero with diversity gains, while it can have a\nlinear-decay-rate exponent according to large deviation theory (LDT) with\nlimited receiver sensitivity. Besides, we find that the arbitrary-decay-rate\nqueue length tail distribution with the finite average power consumption exists\nin the Rayleigh fading channel. Then, we generalize the sufficient conditions\nfor the communication system belonging to these three scenarios, respectively.\nMoreover, we apply the above results to analyze the wireless link transmission\nin the Nakagami-m fading channel. Numerical results with approximation validate\nour analysis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 12 Nov 2021 05:51:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 23 Nov 2021 01:22:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-24"}
